
# job control system ( alpha stage )

# write the beginnings of the job control system that can start running
# on mac laptop.

# local jcl config; probably ~/.../jcla/config.ini
# name of status file; job data directory
# stage
# - new - a job name and parameters or a job def/id
# - init - start initializing job elements
# - pre-processing - run system jobs to prepare for fulfilment
# - pre-dependancies - copy remote data, mount remote files, create locks, etc
# - fulfilment - run all the elements of the job, each step in order and any related tasks
# - verification - run any executable to verify the results of the job
# - post-dependancies - copy remote data out, clear locks, archive logs, etc
# - cleanup - delete temp data
# - complete - nothing left to do
# status
# - wait
# - running
# - error
# - recover
# - fail
# -
# sub-status - implement such that status and sub-status can behave as a single value which
#           will match multiple values. is sub-status == 'app running' then status == 'running'
#           and status == 'app running' are both true
# - wait for dependancies
# - app running
# - system running
# state ( multi-value )
# - error - something went wrong, recovery can clear error state
# - fail - recovery had an error, fail cannot be cleared
# - app errors - errors the application encountered
# - system errors - system errors that occurred
# - warnings - warning messages from anywhere
# - process info - all the processes that ran for this job
# - current process - the currently running process
# - current log - the current log
# - all logs - every log generated for this job
# - dependncies - all dependancy relationships and status related to this job
# - dependancy issues - any problem encountered related to dependancies and resolutions
# - recovery - all recovery processes related to this job

job control scheduling....
two types: regular and ad-hoc
regular jobs are scheduled to start based on calendar or other events.
ad-hoc jobs do not have a schedule.
 1. foreign requests ( human or other systems )
 2. internal requests - related to some other job
an instance of a job is created to acomodate the process of executing the programs.
jobs can be part of a session and or stream, the session defines resources available
to a set of related jobs, a stream defines a series of interdepandant jobs.
[ by default use a null session which does not save any session data ]
[ maybe also have a null stream so that jobs can refer to stream features ]
